	<text>
		<front>
			<p>The series of <hi rend="italic">capitula</hi> published here is unknown to both <ref
					target="#de_Bruyne">de Bruyne</ref> and the <ref target="#Ben">Benedictine
					edition</ref> of the Vulgate. Since it is mainly based on de Bruyne's <ref
					target="https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k8537228/f131">B series</ref> (as
				observed by P.-M. Bogaert in <ref target="#descrBog">Bogaert et alii</ref>, pp. 81-82;
				see also below), we label it <hi rend="bold">B(a)_dobips</hi>. Among the manuscripts
				recorded in the DOBiPS database, it occurs only in <hi rend="bold">To</hi> (Tournai,
				Bibliothèque du Séminaire, MS 1), the first volume (the second being lost) of the
				so-called Bible of Lobbes, produced at the eponymous Belgian abbey in the late 11th
				century. <lb/><lb/>As in the case of 2 Regum (here) and 3 Regum (here), B(a) draws
				mainly on de Bruyne's <ref
					target="https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k8537228/f131">B series</ref>,
				dividing its <hi rend="italic">capitula</hi> into two or more titles and adding
				further details, often taken from the <ref
					target="https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k8537228/f130">A series</ref>.
				<lb/>For example, B's <hi rend="italic">cap.</hi> 2 gives rise to B(a)'s <hi
					rend="italic">cap.</hi> 68-70, 73, and 75; <hi rend="italic">cap.</hi> 71-72 and
				74 are probably inspired by A's <hi rend="italic">cap.</hi> 60-62, though with only
				slight lexical overlap. The text of these <hi rend="italic">capitula</hi> is as
				follows: <list>
					<item>B <list>
							<item>2 De ioram fratre ochoziae et de helia ubi iordanem diuidit et in
								caelum rapitur et de helisaei <lb/> reditu et diuisione iordanis et
								de ioram et iosaphat et rege edom ubi dimicauerunt contra moab
								<lb/>ubi aquae terram sine pluuia repleuerunt</item>
						</list></item>
					<item>B(a)<list>
							<item>68 De morte ochoziȩ et de ioram fratre eius</item>
							<item>69 De helia ubi iordanen diuidit et in cȩlum rapitur</item>
							<item>70 De helisei reditu et diuisione iordanis et heliȩ quȩsitu</item>
							<item>71 De aquis amarissimis ad uerbum helisei in dulcorem
								conuersis</item>
							<item>72 Puerorum contumelia quos heliseus maledixit</item>
							<item>73 De ioram et iosaphat et rege edom ubi dimicare ierunt contra
								moab</item>
							<item>74 Tres reges cum exercitu siti laborantes ad heliseum
								descendunt</item>
							<item>75 Vbi aquȩ terram sine pluuia repleuerunt</item>
						</list></item>
					<item>A<list>
							<item>60 Miraculum helisei in hierico ubi inuocauit dominum et conuertit
								aquas in dulcedinem</item>
							<item>61 Pueri contumeliam fecerunt heliseo qui maledixit eis et
								exierunt duo ursi de saltu et lacerati <lb/> sunt figura est
								adueniens quod fuit uespasianus et titus</item>
							<item>62 Bellum regum in quo laborabant siti unde quaesitus est heliseus
								et orauit et data est aqua <lb/>sed unus regum filium suum
								primogenitum super murum obtulit holocaustum et recessit ab eo
								<lb/>israhel pro hoc malo</item>
						</list></item>
				</list> The numbering (66-139) continues that of book 3.<lb/><lb/>The point in the
				text of 4 Regum where To places the chapter number corresponding to each <hi
					rend="italic">capitulum</hi> can be accessed either by clicking on the two-page
				icon next to each <hi rend="italic">capitulum</hi> number, or by clicking on the
				"Passi paralleli" thumbnail (in the right-hand panel of the "Testo di lettura"
				screen).</p>
		</front>
